Comparison: In the series, Daenerys asks Tyrion what she should do with Jorah. But in the books, Tyrion and Daenerys have not yet met at this point, though it has been confirmed to happen in the following novel. In the series, Qyburn tells Cersei that she will have a trial for fornication, treason, incest, and murder of Robert Baratheon. In the books, Cersei is accused not only of the crimes of fornication, treason, incest and Robert's murder, but also with the murder of the previous High Septon (who was killed by Osney Kettleblack at Cersei's command).

Scene: Ser Kevan is the Hand of the King
Comparison: In the series, Qyburn informs Cersei that Pycelle has summoned Ser Kevan back to King's Landing as the Hand of the King. In the books, Ser Kevan does come back to preside over the small council after Cersei's arrest, but in the position of Lord Regent, not Hand of the King. Since Tommen is older in the show, he does not need a Regent anymore; Cersei was Queen Mother, and Kevan can't be Lord Regent. In the books, after becoming the Regent, Kevan appoints Mace Tyrell as the Hand of the King. Also, Qyburn is dismissed from Kevan's council.

Scene: Theon admits that Rickon and Bran are alive
Comparison: In the series, Sansa urged Theon to talks about Rickon and Bran. Theon then tells Sansa that he didn't kill them and it was two farm boys that he killed. In the books, Theon doesn't tell Sansa that Bran and Rickon are alive, as they have not seen each other since she left Winterfell.

Scene: Boltons sends a small army out against Stannis' army
Comparison: In the series, Roose Bolton suggest to wait for Stannis' army to weaken and that they stay behind within their walls. But Ramsay suggest that he leads a small army of 20 men to attack Stannis' army. In the books, Roose Bolton also lets out a host to fight Stannis in the snow, though it is a much larger one, instead of a small raiding party led by Ramsay. Roose only does so when forced due to the rising tensions in the castle: The Freys and Manderlys are at each others' throats, so he decides it may be better if they abandon the castle and attack Stannis in the snow.

Scene: Daenerys asks Tyrion to advice her
Comparison: In the series, Daenerys asks Tyrion to advice her to get the Iron Throne. In the books, the two haven't met yet and Daenerys never asked Tyrion to advice her on anything.

Scene: Daenerys wants to break the wheel of the Great Houses
Comparison: In the series, Daenerys tells Tyrion that she wants to break the wheel of the Houses. In the books, though Daenerys is empathetic to the slaves and the poor, she never implies an end to feudalism were she to rule the Seven Kingdoms, which she does in the show when she talks about "breaking the wheel" of Great Houses that she presumes is crushing the smallfolk, including her own House Targaryen in the list.
